Writing Queries on Dune Analytics

4 steps

Now that you have a better understanding of Dune Analytics, we will now transition to the more technical aspects of Dune which is writing queries!

We will start off by writing basic, simple queries, gradually building off our knowledge. To ensure that you are able to read and write queries, we will first begin with a refresher on SQL syntax which is essential for querying blockchain data effectively on Dune!

Whether you're a beginner or an experienced data analyst, this will equip you with the necessary knowledge to navigate Dune Analytics where you are able to discover and uncover valuable blockchain insights!

Let’s begin!
Join us on Discord

Helpful prior knowledge

  • There are no pre-requisites

Learning Outcomes

By the end of this, you will be able to:

  • Write basic queries on Dune Analytics
  • Build visualizations from query results
  • Build a dashboard with multiple visualizations

Tutorial Steps

Total steps: 4

  • Step 1: Refresher on SQL Syntax

    Previously, we have introduced the non-technical aspects of Dune Analytics and how Dune Analytics benefits developers as a whole.

    We will now transition to the more technical aspects of Dune where we will first start off with a refresher on SQL syntax to ensure that you are able to understand and apply the SQL syntax when working with Dune Analytics!

    Refresher on SQL Syntax

    Next, we will be going through some important SQL keywords for you to get started on writing queries on Dune.

    SELECT Basics

    SELECT keyword is used when we would like to retrieve specific values from a table. 

    SELECT is also often used in conjunction with the following SQL keywords when writing queries.

    • FROM keyword is used to define which table we would like to retrieve values from
    • WHERE keyword allows us to filter records from our table and records that fulfil a specified condition are returned
    • LIMIT keyword is used to define the number of rows that will be returned.
    SELECT * 
FROM my_table
WHERE temperature > 38
LIMIT 10
    SQL

    In the above query snippet, the SELECT keyword is used as we would like to retrieve values and the * asterisk is used as we would like to return all columns from our query.

    The FROM keyword is used to define that we would like to retrieve values from “my_table”.

    We also introduced the WHERE keyword to filter our records and only the rows with the temperature column above 38 are returned!

    Lastly, LIMIT is used to define how many rows will be returned and in this instance, 10 rows would be returned!

    ORDER BY Basics

    Next, we will discuss the ORDER BY keyword.

    The ORDER BY keyword is used in SQL queries to sort data returned by a query either in an ascending or descending order. By default, if we were to omit this keyword, the data will be sorted in an ascending order. 

    SELECT * 
FROM my_table
WHERE temperature > 38
ORDER BY temperature DESC
LIMIT 10
    SQL

    Using the previous code snippet for reference, we introduce the ORDER BY keyword to our query. After performing the condition check, the data is sorted in a descending order and the top 10 rows with the highest temperature will be returned! 

    GROUP BY Basics

    Lastly, we will discuss the GROUP BY keyword.

    The GROUP BY keyword is used to organise data that have the same attribute vales.

    Often, we will also see this keyword being used in conjunction with aggregate functions such as SUM, AVG, COUNT to generate summary reports from our table.

    SELECT country, COUNT(userId) 
FROM my_table
GROUP BY country
ORDER BY COUNT(userId) DESC
LIMIT 10
    SQL

    Building off the previous code snippet as reference, we introduce the GROUP BY keyword to our query.

    The following query now returns the 10 countries with the highest number of users sorted high to low.

    Now that you have a better understanding of SQL syntax from this refresher, we are now ready to construct and write our first queries on Dune!

  • Step 2: Write Your First Query on Dune

    After completing the refresher in Step 1, we are now ready to write queries on Dune. To begin, head over to the Dune homepage and proceed to sign up for a new Dune account if you do not currently have one.

    Once you have signed up and have logged in to your Dune account, you will be directed to the Dune homepage.

    Next, click on “+” icon as shown and select the “New dashboard” option

    You should then be shown to an empty dashboard page as shown below. The dashboard page is where we will be housing all our upcoming queries and visualizations! 

    Once you have successfully created your dashboard, next click on the “+” icon and select “New Query”. You should be redirected to the Dune editor page as shown where we will begin writing our SQL queries to analyze blockchain data!

    Query - Latest Price of Ethereum

    For our very first query, we will be querying the most updated Ethereum price on Dune!

    Under the dune tab, start by entering “prices.usd” as shown and you should observe the 2 datasets available for us to query where we will be querying the “usd_latest” dataset.

    Next, click on the “usd_latest” dataset which shows the latest prices of tokens in USD. You should also observe the available fields for query along with the different field data types!

    Further, by hovering over the icon as shown, a table preview would be shown to get a better understanding of the table schema and the different data types!

    With a better understanding of the dataset that we will be querying, we are now ready to write the query on Dune!

    Copy the following code snippet and paste it on the Dune query editor. Next, click on ‘Run’ and you should observe the latest price of Ethereum under your query results!

    SELECT price as eth_price
FROM prices.usd_latest
WHERE symbol='ETH'
ORDER BY minute DESC
LIMIT 1
    SQL

    This query retrieves the latest price of Ethereum (ETH) in USD from a table called "prices.usd_latest." It selects the "price" column and renames it as "eth_price." The results are then sorted in a descending order by minute and returns the latest price.

    Next, we will be creating a simple visualization from our query results! Click on the “New visualization” tab and select “Counter”.

    Next, click on “Add visualization” and you should observe a counter visualization indicating the price of Ethereum.

    Proceed to configure the visualization options as shown and you should observe the following!

    Next, scroll up and click on “Save” to save your queries. Name the query “latest_eth_price”.

    Once you have saved the query, proceed to head back to the library page and click on your dashboard titled “My First Dashboard”.

    Next, click on “Edit” followed by “Add visualization” and add your latest visualization to your dashboard page. The visualization name should be “ETH Price” and once you have added the visualization, you should observe the following output!

  • Step 3: Query Latest Transactions on Ethereum

    For our second query, we will be querying the latest transactions from the Ethereum blockchain, specifically the top 10 transactions with the highest gas prices.

    To get started, create a new query by clicking on the “+” icon and select “New Query”.

    Next, before writing the query, let’s analyze the datasets available for us. Enter “ethereum” under the dataset search field and you should observe a list of Ethereum-based datasets as shown where we will be specifically working on the transactions table.

    You can also hover over the icon to get a table preview of the available data types for a better understanding of which fields are available for us to query!

    Copy the following code snippet and paste it on the Dune query editor. Next, click on ‘Run’. 

    SELECT block_time, hash, (gas_price/1e18) AS gas_price_eth
FROM ethereum.transactions
WHERE block_time > NOW() - INTERVAL '1' DAY
ORDER BY gas_price DESC
LIMIT 10
    SQL

    This query fetches data from the "ethereum.transactions" table. It selects the block time, hash, and gas price, which we have formatted from Gwei to ETH by dividing it by 1e18. For more information for Ethereum unit conversion, you can head over here.

    As we would only require the latest transactions, we used the WHERE clause which filters the transactions based on their block time, specifically retrieving transactions that have occurred within the last 24 hours.

    The results are then sorted in a descending order based on the gas price. Lastly, we used the LIMIT clause restricting our output to a maximum of 10 transactions.

    Next, we will be creating a simple visualization from our query results similar to Step 2! Click on the “New visualization” tab and select “Table” where you should observe the following output. 

    Proceed to save your query by clicking on “Save”. Name the query “Latest_Transactions_Gas”.

    Once you have saved your query, head over to your dashboard and add the new visualization to your dashboard! Your dashboard should look like the following.

  • Step 4: Query Weekly DEX Volume on Ethereum

    For our final query in this quest, we will query the weekly volumes on decentralized exchanges (DEX) to identify which exchanges have the highest volume weekly.

    A DEX is a peer to peer marketplace where transactions are not officiated by banks, brokers or any other kind of intermediary. Instead, they are simply a set of smart contracts where every DEX transaction is settled directly on the blockchain. An example of a prominent DEX is Uniswap!

    For more information on what a DEX is, you can head over here.

    With a better understanding of how a DEX works, we are now ready to write the query. Start by creating a new query by clicking on the “+” icon and select “New query”.

    Before writing the query, let’s analyze the dataset that we will be working with in order to query the weekly volumes across the decentralized exchanges. On the dataset field, input “dex.trades” and you should observe the table available for us to preview.

    Click on the table and you should see a list of variables along with their respective data types!

    The “dex.trades” table is an example of a Spellbook table available for the Dune community to use where they have standardized and normalized all trading data across all relevant decentralized exchanges.

    With this table, users are now able to easily query trading data without having to go through the hassle to aggregate all the different DEX smart contracts and can directly query the table to build more meaningful insights!

    For more details on the dex.trades table, you can head over here.

    Now that you have a better understanding of the table, we are now ready to write the query!

    Copy the following code snippet and paste it on the query editor.

    SELECT project AS "Project",
ROUND(SUM(CAST(amount_usd AS DOUBLE)) / 1e6) AS usd_volume_million
FROM dex.trades
WHERE block_time > NOW() - INTERVAL '7' day
GROUP BY Project
ORDER BY usd_volume_million DESC
LIMIT 10
    SQL

    Proceed to fill in the placeholder query snippet by yourself to query the weekly volume in millions across DEXs.

    Start by defining the interval on a weekly basis using the WHERE keyword. Next, proceed to group the rows based on the “Project” field and order the “usd_volume_million” field in a descending manner! If you are unsure on how to write the query, you can refer below to understand how the query works!

    Here’s an example of the weekly dex volume query result.

    The query begins by selecting two columns: "project" and "amount_usd." The "project" column represents the name or identifier of a project, while the "amount_usd" column represents the trading amount in USD.

    To calculate the trading volume in millions of USD for each project, the "amount_usd" values are cast to a double data type and summed up. The result is then divided by 1 million and rounded using the ROUND function. The alias "usd_volume_million" is then assigned to this calculated value.

    Next, the query applies a filter using the WHERE clause. It selects only the trades that occurred within the last seven days based on the "block_time" column, which represents the time when each trade was executed. The expression "NOW() - INTERVAL '7' day" calculates the date and time seven days prior to the current time.

    The result set is then grouped by the "Project" column, aggregating the trading volume for each distinct project using the “GROUP BY” keyword.

    To determine the top 10 projects based on trading volume, the query employs an ORDER BY clause. The "usd_volume_million" column is sorted in descending order. Finally, the LIMIT clause is used to restrict the result set to only the first 10 rows.

    In summary, this query provides a snapshot of the top 10 projects by trading volume in the last seven days, denominated in millions.

    Next, we will be creating a visualization to represent the snapshot of weekly DEX volumes. Click on “New visualization” and select the pie chart option. Next, configure the pie chart visualization as shown below.

    Next, save your query and name it “weekly_dex”.

    Once you have saved your query, head over to the dashboard page. Proceed to add the query results and visualization from the “weekly_dex” to your dashboard where you should observe the following output.

    Congratulations Developer! 🎉

    You have successfully built your first Dune dashboard focusing on Ethereum! This achievement demonstrates your understanding of Dune fundamentals and is a great step forward in your analytics journey.

    Keep exploring and expanding your skills with Dune to uncover even more insights from blockchain data.

    Happy Analyzing!! 🚀
